---
// Library section with curated papers and resources
---

<section id="library" class="section-padding">
  <div class="container-max">
    <div class="text-center mb-16 animate-on-scroll">
      <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-mono font-bold mb-6">The Library</h2>
      <p class="text-xl text-charcoal dark:text-dark-text max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        A curated collection of foundational papers, cutting-edge research, and essential resources 
        that shape the landscape of cryptography and privacy-preserving technologies.
      </p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
      <!-- Foundational Papers -->
      <div class="space-y-8 animate-on-scroll">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-mono font-bold text-forest-green dark:text-dark-heading mb-6">
          Foundational Works
        </h3>
        
        <article class="glass-effect rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition-all duration-300">
          <h4 class="font-mono font-bold text-lg text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent mb-2">
            The Knowledge Complexity of Interactive Proof Systems
          </h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/80 dark:text-dark-text/80 mb-3">
            Goldwasser, S., Micali, S., & Rackoff, C. (1989). <em>SIAM Journal on Computing</em>, 18(1), 186-208.
          </p>
          <p class="text-charcoal dark:text-dark-text text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
            The seminal paper that introduced zero-knowledge proofs, fundamentally changing how we think about proving knowledge without revealing information.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm italic text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent">
            My note: This paper laid the theoretical foundation for everything we do in privacy-preserving cryptography today. The elegance of the zero-knowledge property continues to inspire new applications.
          </p>
        </article>
        
        <article class="glass-effect rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition-all duration-300">
          <h4 class="font-mono font-bold text-lg text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent mb-2">
            Quadratic Span Programs and Succinct NIZKs without PCPs
          </h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/80 dark:text-dark-text/80 mb-3">
            Gennaro, R., Gentry, C., Parno, B., & Raykova, M. (2013). <em>EUROCRYPT 2013</em>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-charcoal dark:text-dark-text text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
            Introduced Quadratic Arithmetic Programs (QAPs), the mathematical foundation underlying zk-SNARKs and modern zero-knowledge proof systems.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm italic text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent">
            My note: QAPs bridge the gap between circuit satisfiability and polynomial commitments. Understanding this transformation is crucial for anyone working with zk-SNARKs.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Recent Research -->
      <div class="space-y-8 animate-on-scroll" style="animation-delay: 0.2s">
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-mono font-bold text-forest-green dark:text-dark-heading mb-6">
          Recent Advances
        </h3>
        
        <article class="glass-effect rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition-all duration-300">
          <h4 class="font-mono font-bold text-lg text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent mb-2">
            Plonk: Permutations over Lagrange-bases for Oecumenical Noninteractive arguments of Knowledge
          </h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/80 dark:text-dark-text/80 mb-3">
            Gabizon, A., Williamson, Z. J., & Ciobotaru, O. (2019). <em>IACR ePrint Archive</em>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-charcoal dark:text-dark-text text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
            Introduced a universal and updatable zk-SNARK construction that doesn't require a trusted setup per circuit, revolutionizing practical ZK applications.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm italic text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent">
            My note: PLONK's universal setup is a game-changer for production systems. The permutation argument technique is particularly elegant and has inspired many subsequent works.
          </p>
        </article>
        
        <article class="glass-effect rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition-all duration-300">
          <h4 class="font-mono font-bold text-lg text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent mb-2">
            Halo: Recursive Proof Composition without a Trusted Setup
          </h4>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/80 dark:text-dark-text/80 mb-3">
            Bowe, S., Grigg, J., & Hopwood, D. (2019). <em>IACR ePrint Archive</em>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-charcoal dark:text-dark-text text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
            Demonstrated how to achieve recursive proof composition without trusted setups, enabling infinite scalability for blockchain applications.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm italic text-matcha-green dark:text-dark-accent">
            My note: Halo's approach to recursion through inner product arguments is mathematically beautiful. It opens the door to truly scalable blockchain architectures.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
    
